author.name: Moldovan Family Judaica Collection (University of Pennsylvania)

support.watermark: "Trevoie" along the gutter (examples, f. 161, f. 149) with a bell below it (example f. 129).

supportDesc.extent: 163 leaves : 185 x 130 (160 x 100) mm bound to 190 x 135 mm

collation.p: Paper, v + 163 + vi; 1¹² (-1) 2-13¹² 14⁸; modern foliation in pencil, lower left recto, [1-163]; modern pagination in ink, upper outer corners, [1-321] (f. 2r-162v); references in this record are to the foliation.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 23-25 long lines; some piyutim are written in a shirah form called "ariaḥ ʻal gabe levenah," meaning (in masonry terms) stretcher over a course (see Talmud Bavli Megillah 16b, for example f. 82-84); another shirah form called "ariaḥ ʻal gabe ariaḥ", stretcher over a stretcher is used (for example f. 86r); other standard paragraph formats are used for other piyutim.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in a French-Italian square script, all vocalized; headers written in Ashkenazic cursive in the hand of ʻImanuʼel ben Gad de Milhaud. This scribe was prolific in creation of manuscripts for prayers in the customs of French communities, and he was active in the late 17th and early 18th centuries.

binding.p: Brown sheepskin binding, almost completely intact, likely the original binding.

origin.p: Written in Provence, likely in Carpentras, France, in 5480 (1719-1720) by ʻImanuʼel ben Gad de Milhaud and dated in the year 5480 (f. 1r).

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Yosef de Monteles (inscription inside front cover, approximately 1730-1760).
Presented to The Penn Libraries in 2018 by Joseph and Susan Moldovan (C'76).
